  "allophone_rules": [
    {
      "id": "TA_VOICE_tɕa",
      "phonemes": [
        "tɕa"
      ],
      "surface": "dʑa",
      "word_initial": false,
      "notes": "Malayalam inherits the Dravidian intervocalic/post-nasal voicing rules from its parent (ta): plosives are voiceless word-initially and when geminated, voiced between vowels and after a nasal (Asher & Kumari 1997: 405-406; Krishnamurti 2003: 4.2) — പകർച്ച [paɡar-], മരുതം [marud̪am]. It differs from Tamil in ONE realisation: the palatal ⟨ച⟩ does not lenite to [s] between vowels, it voices to [dʑ] like the rest of the series (Asher & Kumari 1997: 405-406). These rules override the inherited TA_VOICE_tɕ* by id."
    },
    {
      "id": "TA_VOICE_tɕ",
      "phonemes": [
